    editorial: { intuition: "The longest palindromic subsequence of s equals the LCS of s and its reverse.", bruteForce: "Check all subsequences for palindrome property. Time: O(2^n × n).", betterApproach: "DP on substrings: dp[i][j] = LPS length of s[i..j].", optimalApproach: "LCS(s, reverse(s)): dp[i][j] = if s[i]==rev[j] then dp[i-1][j-1]+1 else max(dp[i-1][j], dp[i][j-1]). Time: O(n²), Space: O(n²) or O(n) with space optimization.", dryRun: "s='bbbab', rev='babbB':\nLCS dp table gives answer 4.", timeComplexity: "O(n²)", spaceComplexity: "O(n) with space optimization", alternativeSolution: "Direct DP: dp[i][j] = LPS of s[i..j]. Base: dp[i][i]=1. Iterate by length.", interviewTips: "Know the LCS connection. This transforms a subsequence problem into a well-known DP problem.", commonMistakes: "Confusing subsequence with substring. Wrong DP transition when characters don't match." },
