    hints: ["Multiply digit by digit like grade-school multiplication.","Result of num1[i] × num2[j] goes to position [i+j, i+j+1] in the result array.","Handle carry propagation and leading zeros."],
    editorial: { intuition: "Grade-school multiplication: multiply each digit pair and accumulate in a result array, handling carries.", bruteForce: "Same as optimal — digit-by-digit multiplication.", betterApproach: "Same.", optimalApproach: "Create result array of size m+n (max possible digits). For each pair (i,j): result[i+j+1] += digit1[i] * digit2[j]. Propagate carries right to left. Skip leading zeros. Time: O(m×n), Space: O(m+n).", dryRun: "123 × 456:\nresult=[0,0,0,0,0,0]\n3×6=18→result[5]+=18, 3×5=15→result[4]+=15, 3×4=12→result[3]+=12\n2×6=12→result[4]+=12, 2×5=10→result[3]+=10, 2×4=8→result[2]+=8\n1×6=6→result[3]+=6, 1×5=5→result[2]+=5, 1×4=4→result[1]+=4\nPropagate carries → '056088' → '56088' ✓", timeComplexity: "O(m × n)", spaceComplexity: "O(m + n)", alternativeSolution: "Karatsuba multiplication for O(n^1.585) — overkill for this constraint but good to mention.", interviewTips: "Index math is tricky. Draw out the multiplication grid during the interview.", commonMistakes: "Not handling the '0' case. Wrong index mapping (i+j vs i+j+1). Leading zeros in result." },
